1
00:00:13,518 --> 00:00:17,087
[Fire crackling]

2
00:00:19,324 --> 00:00:21,463
For this, to me,

3
00:00:21,464 --> 00:00:25,431
is what new Australia means

4
00:00:25,432 --> 00:00:28,266
to the landless,

5
00:00:28,268 --> 00:00:30,986
the homeless,

6
00:00:30,987 --> 00:00:34,478
to those who long to be manly,

7
00:00:34,479 --> 00:00:37,033
to be true,

8
00:00:37,034 --> 00:00:40,627
to be what men should be,

9
00:00:40,628 --> 00:00:45,264
to live simply, to work hardly,

10
00:00:45,266 --> 00:00:48,744
to win not the gold that poisons

11
00:00:48,745 --> 00:00:51,246
but the home that saves,

12
00:00:51,248 --> 00:00:54,049
to secure the little ones,

13
00:00:54,050 --> 00:00:57,588
the rearing that is the right
of everyone

14
00:00:57,589 --> 00:01:00,471
brought by us into the world.

15
00:01:00,901 --> 00:01:02,468
We can do it

16
00:01:02,470 --> 00:01:05,370
if we only dare.

17
00:01:07,977 --> 00:01:10,245
Again.

18
00:01:11,329 --> 00:01:15,343
For this, to me,
is what new Australia means.

19
00:01:15,344 --> 00:01:18,712
[Pensive instrumental music]

20
00:01:47,063 --> 00:01:50,766
[Birds squawking]

21
00:01:51,901 --> 00:01:54,870
Birds have been here too.

22
00:02:01,508 --> 00:02:02,708
[Grunts]

23
00:02:02,710 --> 00:02:04,093
[Rustling]

24
00:02:04,094 --> 00:02:05,193
Dad.

25
00:02:05,195 --> 00:02:08,697
[Grunting]

26
00:02:10,110 --> 00:02:12,444
[Groans]

27
00:02:19,946 --> 00:02:21,882
Dad!

28
00:02:21,883 --> 00:02:24,483
Are you all right?

29
00:02:24,782 --> 00:02:26,716
[Groans]

30
00:02:32,456 --> 00:02:34,993
Bloody colony.

31
00:02:35,994 --> 00:02:37,860
Dad!

32
00:02:42,547 --> 00:02:43,413
[Horse groans]

33
00:02:43,438 --> 00:02:45,796
Stupid bloody thing.

34
00:02:45,797 --> 00:02:47,930
[Gunshot]

35
00:02:54,446 --> 00:02:56,382
Tie them to that,

36
00:02:56,383 --> 00:02:58,350
that branch.

37
00:02:59,157 --> 00:03:03,312
Only one way in there, and I don't
want anyone else falling foul of it.

38
00:03:32,985 --> 00:03:36,688
[Rhythmic tapping]

39
00:03:50,985 --> 00:03:53,286
Oh!

40
00:04:06,767 --> 00:04:09,769
[Bird squawking]

41
00:04:10,250 --> 00:04:13,617
Try zamba.
Rub it in.

42
00:04:13,618 --> 00:04:17,444
Burns, pimples, piles.

43
00:04:17,469 --> 00:04:21,004
You clown.
[Laughing]

44
00:04:32,646 --> 00:04:35,114
Everything's changing.

45
00:04:39,321 --> 00:04:41,593
I miss her too, Tom.

46
00:04:42,726 --> 00:04:45,805
[Sighs]

47
00:04:50,129 --> 00:04:53,631
[Crickets chirping]

48
00:05:39,214 --> 00:05:41,983
[Sighs]

49
00:06:19,580 --> 00:06:22,641
[Horse chuffing]

50
00:06:26,290 --> 00:06:28,880
Dad, the rabbiter's here.

51
00:06:31,064 --> 00:06:34,727
- Here. Take them.
- Thanks.

52
00:06:53,649 --> 00:06:55,747
What happened to the horse?

53
00:06:56,620 --> 00:06:58,617
You going somewhere?

54
00:06:58,618 --> 00:07:01,175
They're all digging for gold.

55
00:07:02,305 --> 00:07:04,624
Still planning the ground,
I reckon.

56
00:07:04,625 --> 00:07:07,672
That's not why we came out here.

57
00:07:07,993 --> 00:07:11,796
Useless bloody sack of dirt,
they shatted on us.

58
00:07:11,797 --> 00:07:13,320
They can have it.

59
00:07:13,321 --> 00:07:15,087
It's god's land.

60
00:07:15,089 --> 00:07:17,062
He'll provide.

61
00:07:17,500 --> 00:07:19,797
There's no god here.

62
00:07:20,750 --> 00:07:24,648
God cursed this whole bloody
country for our sins.

63
00:07:31,110 --> 00:07:34,852
Reckon I might pick up a bit
of work on the railroad.

64
00:07:41,594 --> 00:07:42,527
Connolly's railroad...

65
00:07:42,529 --> 00:07:45,725
You'll do the same
if you got any sense.

66
00:07:46,930 --> 00:07:50,199
It's money.
I know you're needing that.

67
00:07:51,903 --> 00:07:53,970
Charlie.

68
00:08:07,735 --> 00:08:10,359
I'm in need of a...

69
00:08:11,243 --> 00:08:13,836
a few cartridges.

70
00:08:22,946 --> 00:08:24,898
Here.

71
00:08:26,461 --> 00:08:29,629
That's all I got
till I get to town.

72
00:08:46,141 --> 00:08:48,467
Good luck to you, Nat.

73
00:09:00,922 --> 00:09:03,711
God be with you, Charlie.

74
00:10:28,540 --> 00:10:31,530
We can't keep doing this, dad.

75
00:10:33,368 --> 00:10:35,235
The rabbiter's right.

76
00:10:35,236 --> 00:10:37,358
It's money we need.

77
00:10:37,383 --> 00:10:39,972
God will provide.

78
00:10:49,297 --> 00:10:51,762
[Horses neighing]

79
00:10:52,055 --> 00:10:54,711
What are we going to do
without a horse?

80
00:10:56,852 --> 00:10:58,251
I won't discuss it.

81
00:10:58,253 --> 00:11:00,294
What about Tom?

82
00:11:00,981 --> 00:11:02,848
What about me?

83
00:11:02,849 --> 00:11:06,613
You've your family to think
about before yourself.

84
00:11:06,638 --> 00:11:09,379
A man's got to marry me
in a corn sack.

85
00:11:09,380 --> 00:11:11,206
Marry?

86
00:11:11,231 --> 00:11:13,191
You're not marrying, girl.

87
00:11:13,192 --> 00:11:17,184
You're needed here, and this
is where you're staying.

88
00:11:19,044 --> 00:11:21,133
It's finished, dad.

89
00:11:22,477 --> 00:11:24,677
It's over.

90
00:11:24,950 --> 00:11:26,355
Even mom knew.

91
00:11:26,356 --> 00:11:28,426
You'll keep your mouth shut!

92
00:11:28,427 --> 00:11:30,105
- Dad.
- What?

93
00:11:30,106 --> 00:11:31,519
What is it, little man?

94
00:11:31,520 --> 00:11:33,654
You think you've got
what it takes?

95
00:11:33,656 --> 00:11:36,043
What are you going to do?

96
00:11:36,044 --> 00:11:37,344
Nothing.

97
00:11:37,541 --> 00:11:41,176
[Dog barking]

98
00:11:43,106 --> 00:11:45,074
Hello?

99
00:11:46,950 --> 00:11:49,153
Hello in there?

100
00:11:50,669 --> 00:11:52,019
Come away from there.

101
00:11:52,020 --> 00:11:53,352
Come.

102
00:11:57,924 --> 00:12:00,893
[Door creaking]

103
00:12:12,052 --> 00:12:13,668
What can we do for you?

104
00:12:13,669 --> 00:12:15,836
We have a sick boy here.

105
00:12:16,552 --> 00:12:20,269
Won't last long if we don't get
some shelter for the night.

106
00:12:20,294 --> 00:12:23,545
He's concerned
for the boy's welfare.

107
00:12:25,153 --> 00:12:27,420
Be on our way in the morning.

108
00:12:28,911 --> 00:12:30,477
Go on.

109
00:12:32,667 --> 00:12:34,411
Make way.

110
00:12:43,739 --> 00:12:45,763
There you go, Jimmy.

111
00:12:46,341 --> 00:12:47,957
Yeah.

112
00:12:47,958 --> 00:12:50,191
You'll be all right, son.

113
00:12:50,661 --> 00:12:52,894
Sarah,

114
00:12:52,895 --> 00:12:54,698
make some tea.

115
00:12:56,810 --> 00:12:58,371
What happened?

116
00:12:58,372 --> 00:13:02,246
Hit him on his way up to the
gold fields four days ago.

117
00:13:02,247 --> 00:13:05,215
Grace of god, we found you.

118
00:13:05,217 --> 00:13:08,246
He wouldn't have made it
through the night.

119
00:13:08,247 --> 00:13:10,280
Henry Wilson.

120
00:13:10,282 --> 00:13:12,415
This is Carver.

121
00:13:12,552 --> 00:13:13,771
Nat Dawn.

122
00:13:13,771 --> 00:13:15,418
My son, Tom.

123
00:13:15,419 --> 00:13:17,419
Daughter, Sarah.

124
00:13:18,529 --> 00:13:20,318
Go help your sister.

125
00:13:22,474 --> 00:13:24,160
Come.

126
00:13:24,161 --> 00:13:26,327
Sit by the fire.

127
00:13:29,583 --> 00:13:31,629
Warm yourselves.

128
00:13:31,630 --> 00:13:33,536
Excuse me.

129
00:13:39,716 --> 00:13:42,947
We'll move the boy
out the back in the morning.

130
00:13:44,005 --> 00:13:46,606
It'll be gone tomorrow.

131
00:13:55,048 --> 00:13:57,528
Your mother always said,

132
00:13:57,529 --> 00:14:00,590
"Never turn away strangers."

133
00:14:00,591 --> 00:14:04,106
"They might be angels in disguise."

134
00:14:16,177 --> 00:14:17,817
Thank you, miss.

135
00:14:18,122 --> 00:14:20,419
Very much obliged.

136
00:14:27,564 --> 00:14:30,950
Some interesting items you have
around the place here, Nat.

137
00:14:30,951 --> 00:14:33,802
We brought a fair bit with us.

138
00:14:33,802 --> 00:14:36,583
Oh, she was impressive
when she first went up.

139
00:14:36,584 --> 00:14:38,185
You a carpenter?

140
00:14:38,185 --> 00:14:41,949
I was a teacher in London.

141
00:14:41,950 --> 00:14:43,809
Been back?

142
00:14:44,974 --> 00:14:47,021
You're not missing much.

143
00:14:47,021 --> 00:14:51,091
Seen the boers
living better in South Africa.

144
00:14:52,552 --> 00:14:53,771
Is the mother...

145
00:14:53,771 --> 00:14:55,871
she passed away.

146
00:14:56,427 --> 00:14:58,622
A month now.

147
00:14:59,279 --> 00:15:01,513
I'm sorry.

148
00:15:03,240 --> 00:15:05,278
So you were in the war?

149
00:15:05,279 --> 00:15:06,978
We were.

150
00:15:07,310 --> 00:15:09,410
- And the boy?
- Yeah.

151
00:15:09,412 --> 00:15:12,887
Thought he'd come home
a bloody hero.

152
00:15:12,888 --> 00:15:14,490
Silly bugger.

153
00:15:14,490 --> 00:15:16,385
No.

154
00:15:17,617 --> 00:15:19,806
I'll check the horses.

155
00:15:20,279 --> 00:15:21,778
Horses are fine.

156
00:15:21,780 --> 00:15:24,114
I'll just check.

157
00:15:24,116 --> 00:15:27,317
Let you swells catch up.

158
00:15:28,269 --> 00:15:30,583
[Door creaking]

159
00:15:33,872 --> 00:15:35,907
Don't worry about him.

160
00:15:36,607 --> 00:15:39,214
Look, we could
help you out a bit.

161
00:15:40,341 --> 00:15:42,810
Picked up a few tricks
along the way.

162
00:15:42,810 --> 00:15:45,365
Return your hospitality.

163
00:15:46,427 --> 00:15:49,400
I'd have to think about it.

164
00:15:50,091 --> 00:15:54,041
We don't even get swaggies
coming through anymore.

165
00:15:54,041 --> 00:15:55,493
Endangered species.

166
00:15:55,494 --> 00:15:57,661
Poor bastards.

167
00:15:58,228 --> 00:16:00,807
I'm with Tom Mooney, myself.

168
00:16:00,807 --> 00:16:02,243
Mooney?

169
00:16:02,244 --> 00:16:04,471
Yankee. Socialist.

170
00:16:04,471 --> 00:16:06,518
Every man should have a vote.

171
00:16:06,518 --> 00:16:10,119
Farm and rifle.

172
00:16:18,033 --> 00:16:21,478
It's what God
brought us here for.

173
00:16:21,932 --> 00:16:25,300
Didn't think to find
anyone this far out.

174
00:16:25,302 --> 00:16:29,611
I figured we'd be planting poor little
Jimmy in the ground by morning.

175
00:16:29,612 --> 00:16:33,079
Reckon you'd call it Providence.

176
00:16:39,654 --> 00:16:42,229
Well, I guess we could do
with a hand.

177
00:16:42,230 --> 00:16:43,962
We don't have much.

178
00:16:43,963 --> 00:16:46,664
I appreciate it.
I really do.

179
00:16:47,455 --> 00:16:51,821
The minute the boy's well enough
to ride, we'll be on our way.

180
00:16:51,822 --> 00:16:54,374
We'll earn our keep.

181
00:16:56,900 --> 00:16:59,000
They're soldiers.

182
00:16:59,416 --> 00:17:01,983
They're going to stay
to help out.

183
00:17:02,353 --> 00:17:06,024
What drives somebody
to go halfway around the world

184
00:17:06,025 --> 00:17:08,959
to kill people
they don't even know?

185
00:17:09,266 --> 00:17:10,398
[Breathing heavily]

186
00:17:10,423 --> 00:17:13,127
[Groaning quietly]

187
00:17:13,127 --> 00:17:15,072
Don't do that.

188
00:17:38,018 --> 00:17:39,986
Come here.

189
00:17:39,988 --> 00:17:42,355
Give me that.

190
00:17:51,502 --> 00:17:54,915
Well, this was
a pretty good knife once, eh?

191
00:17:54,916 --> 00:17:59,374
Never let a blade
go blunt too long.

192
00:18:04,666 --> 00:18:07,314
Everything all right, Tom?

193
00:18:07,923 --> 00:18:10,033
With the farm?

194
00:18:10,033 --> 00:18:11,908
With your dad?

195
00:18:12,752 --> 00:18:14,452
I suppose.

196
00:18:15,166 --> 00:18:17,533
We're here to help you, son.

197
00:18:17,970 --> 00:18:21,024
We're here to help you
and your dad out.

198
00:18:21,025 --> 00:18:24,236
So if there's anything you need
or anything you want to tell me,

199
00:18:24,236 --> 00:18:26,136
you can.

200
00:18:26,744 --> 00:18:29,477
You know that, don't you?

201
00:18:29,478 --> 00:18:31,542
Yeah.

202
00:18:32,877 --> 00:18:34,822
Reckon you could finish this up?

203
00:18:34,823 --> 00:18:36,650
Yeah.

204
00:18:37,681 --> 00:18:38,728
Yeah.

205
00:18:38,728 --> 00:18:43,110
Reckon you can turn your hand
at just about anything, Tom.

206
00:18:46,728 --> 00:18:49,517
[Groans]

207
00:19:21,298 --> 00:19:23,565
[Gunshot]

208
00:19:28,088 --> 00:19:31,390
[Gunshot]

209
00:19:38,598 --> 00:19:42,201
[Flies buzzing]

210
00:19:57,134 --> 00:20:00,369
[Gunshot]

211
00:20:22,884 --> 00:20:25,782
Do you think
they killed lots of boers?

212
00:20:27,463 --> 00:20:30,727
It's perfectly obvious
that man's a murderer.

213
00:20:30,728 --> 00:20:32,762
[Gunshot]

214
00:20:35,134 --> 00:20:39,353
That boy's going to die here, and we're
all going to be chopped up with an ax.

215
00:20:39,354 --> 00:20:41,392
Tom.

216
00:20:50,392 --> 00:20:54,774
Nat, I reckon we should
start again from scratch,

217
00:20:54,775 --> 00:20:57,005
if that's all right with you.

218
00:20:58,369 --> 00:21:00,470
You do what you think's best.

219
00:21:00,955 --> 00:21:04,456
Tom and I have to check
some traps.

220
00:21:06,892 --> 00:21:10,759
I'd appreciate it
if you stayed away from there.

221
00:21:15,680 --> 00:21:17,972
You have the balls.

222
00:21:19,289 --> 00:21:20,755
Tom.

223
00:21:40,289 --> 00:21:43,925
[Mumbling indistinctly]

224
00:22:02,110 --> 00:22:03,532
[Gasps]

225
00:22:03,532 --> 00:22:05,632
Who are you?

226
00:22:10,118 --> 00:22:11,719
I'm Sarah.

227
00:22:11,953 --> 00:22:15,292
Love a boy back to life, is it?

228
00:22:19,743 --> 00:22:21,652
Excuse me.

229
00:22:22,899 --> 00:22:24,992
Excuse me.

230
00:22:37,750 --> 00:22:41,953
Bloody thirsty work
building your locker for you.

231
00:23:02,282 --> 00:23:05,101
And you check that one.

232
00:23:12,821 --> 00:23:14,689
Empty.

233
00:23:18,375 --> 00:23:21,640
Well, they can't all be empty,
can they?

234
00:23:39,953 --> 00:23:41,587
[Laughs]

235
00:23:41,589 --> 00:23:43,797
Whoa!
Dad!

236
00:23:43,797 --> 00:23:46,531
This is pretty good!

237
00:23:52,710 --> 00:23:54,538
Very impressive.

238
00:23:54,538 --> 00:23:55,804
[Laughs]

239
00:23:56,428 --> 00:23:59,582
Mr. Henry, look at me.

240
00:24:00,569 --> 00:24:02,748
Traps empty?

241
00:24:03,217 --> 00:24:05,943
How's the boy doing?

242
00:24:09,077 --> 00:24:10,850
Sarah?

243
00:24:12,874 --> 00:24:14,248
How's his fever?

244
00:24:14,249 --> 00:24:16,416
- The fever broke earlier.
- Good.

245
00:24:16,418 --> 00:24:18,366
I mean, he looks better,

246
00:24:18,366 --> 00:24:20,475
but he's still...

247
00:24:31,249 --> 00:24:33,092
We'll move him out
to the stables.

248
00:24:33,093 --> 00:24:35,545
Make up a bed for him.

249
00:24:42,428 --> 00:24:44,428
Hey, kid.

250
00:25:11,889 --> 00:25:13,623
[Grunts]

251
00:25:13,625 --> 00:25:16,436
[Breathing heavily]

252
00:25:16,436 --> 00:25:18,369
Sarah.

253
00:25:21,147 --> 00:25:23,549
[Gunshot]

254
00:25:33,439 --> 00:25:35,374
[Gunshot]

255
00:25:47,522 --> 00:25:50,538
You should get the boy
to bag some roos for you.

256
00:25:50,538 --> 00:25:52,238
Outstanding shot.

257
00:25:52,741 --> 00:25:54,505
I shot a wooden boer, dad.

258
00:25:54,506 --> 00:25:55,490
Look.

259
00:25:55,491 --> 00:25:56,670
Boys.

260
00:25:57,452 --> 00:25:59,702
We could take the rifles out
in the morning,

261
00:25:59,702 --> 00:26:01,341
Jimmy's still down.

262
00:26:01,342 --> 00:26:02,936
I shot it off the log.

263
00:26:02,936 --> 00:26:06,046
Come and shoot
some black crows, are you?

264
00:26:06,046 --> 00:26:08,213
Shoot some blackbirds?

265
00:26:08,999 --> 00:26:10,615
What's he talking about?

266
00:26:10,616 --> 00:26:12,397
Nothing.

267
00:26:12,624 --> 00:26:14,191
How about it, Nat?

268
00:26:14,577 --> 00:26:18,428
Carver will stay back and chop
some logs for your new locker.

269
00:26:18,453 --> 00:26:20,529
Eh, Carver?

270
00:26:21,186 --> 00:26:22,474
Yeah.

271
00:26:22,499 --> 00:26:25,045
Sure.
Come on, Tom.

272
00:26:32,796 --> 00:26:34,302
Interesting kid.

273
00:26:34,303 --> 00:26:37,802
Doesn't deserve a man
like that for a father.

274
00:26:37,803 --> 00:26:39,469
What does that mean?

275
00:26:39,858 --> 00:26:41,569
Well, he thinks
he should get it different

276
00:26:41,569 --> 00:26:44,503
just 'cause he's got God
on his side.

277
00:26:44,505 --> 00:26:46,372
Careful, Carver.

278
00:26:46,702 --> 00:26:49,857
Takes three generations
to make a gentleman.

279
00:26:49,858 --> 00:26:53,608
And about three minutes
to unmake him.

280
00:26:56,889 --> 00:26:59,694
We've seen things, Henry,

281
00:26:59,694 --> 00:27:02,370
things other people like.

282
00:27:03,249 --> 00:27:05,528
Counts for something.

283
00:27:07,491 --> 00:27:10,099
Ain't that right?

284
00:27:12,227 --> 00:27:14,227
Yeah.

285
00:27:14,533 --> 00:27:17,200
That's right.

286
00:27:30,522 --> 00:27:33,253
That Jimmy breaking into song yet?

287
00:27:33,278 --> 00:27:37,314
Yeah, he's dancing with a horse.

288
00:27:43,630 --> 00:27:46,824
You were a captain, yes?

289
00:27:46,825 --> 00:27:49,659
Major.

290
00:27:50,044 --> 00:27:52,616
And you, Mr. Carver?

291
00:27:53,256 --> 00:27:55,208
What's it to you?

292
00:27:56,467 --> 00:27:58,537
I'm just interested.

293
00:27:59,123 --> 00:28:01,184
Well, I ain't.

294
00:28:01,859 --> 00:28:04,385
Oh, leave
the glum bastard alone.

295
00:28:04,386 --> 00:28:08,292
He's got a chip on his shoulder
the size of your arm.

296
00:28:17,529 --> 00:28:20,398
[Door creaks]

297
00:28:23,808 --> 00:28:26,559
You look like you're in
some nativity scene.

298
00:28:27,175 --> 00:28:29,275
What?

299
00:28:32,582 --> 00:28:36,087
Well, you seem better, anyway.

300
00:28:39,808 --> 00:28:41,863
Where's Henry?

301
00:28:41,863 --> 00:28:45,264
Inside talking with my dad.

302
00:28:47,285 --> 00:28:50,026
Where is your family?

303
00:28:50,027 --> 00:28:51,957
Don't know.

304
00:28:52,699 --> 00:28:54,799
Same for Henry,

305
00:28:55,394 --> 00:28:59,429
except worse, I guess, 'cause
he had a wife and kids and all.

306
00:28:59,742 --> 00:29:04,732
Henry sort of fell...
fell to drinking there.

307
00:29:04,732 --> 00:29:06,755
That man Carver,
he drinks a lot.

308
00:29:06,756 --> 00:29:08,904
Ah, he's all right.

309
00:29:08,904 --> 00:29:11,471
He's just got that way
about him.

310
00:29:11,472 --> 00:29:14,130
He's had a rough ride,
no mistake.

311
00:29:14,130 --> 00:29:17,427
He got beat senseless by his father
when he was a little Tucker.

312
00:29:17,428 --> 00:29:19,607
Got brought up by his brother

313
00:29:19,607 --> 00:29:22,427
boundary riding
for the squatters and the like.

314
00:29:22,428 --> 00:29:24,694
Where is he now?

315
00:29:40,474 --> 00:29:42,372
Keep a secret?

316
00:29:45,646 --> 00:29:49,048
So up on the gold fields, right,
we gave it a go.

317
00:29:49,050 --> 00:29:53,986
There was nothing there, so Henry said
we'd go back to the city to find work.

318
00:29:55,076 --> 00:29:56,076
What?

319
00:29:57,505 --> 00:30:02,001
Well, they thought
there was nothing there.

320
00:30:02,523 --> 00:30:04,690
Nothing.

321
00:30:04,692 --> 00:30:06,659
Not a bean.

322
00:30:07,288 --> 00:30:13,592
You had diggers up there gnawing in the
same bone for weeks on end dressed in rags.

323
00:30:13,593 --> 00:30:15,398
Bloody grim sight,

324
00:30:15,398 --> 00:30:18,140
what humanity can sink to,

325
00:30:18,640 --> 00:30:21,006
clawing at the dirt

326
00:30:21,031 --> 00:30:24,573
just for the chance
to strike it rich.

327
00:30:26,722 --> 00:30:30,636
I've seen men reduced to states
you wouldn't wish on a hog.

328
00:30:31,371 --> 00:30:34,668
And this is just about
the worse thing I've seen.

329
00:30:34,668 --> 00:30:37,510
You see it in men's eyes,

330
00:30:37,511 --> 00:30:39,277
desperation.

331
00:30:39,277 --> 00:30:42,862
I won't have alcohol
in my house.

332
00:31:03,392 --> 00:31:06,361
We're weak creatures,

333
00:31:06,361 --> 00:31:08,261
corrupted.

334
00:31:08,947 --> 00:31:10,689
I've seen Mr. Connolly drinking.

335
00:31:10,689 --> 00:31:13,244
Is that right, Tom?

336
00:31:14,704 --> 00:31:16,994
Get yourself to bed now, Tupper.

337
00:31:16,994 --> 00:31:18,822
You're going shooting
in the morning, remember?

338
00:31:18,822 --> 00:31:20,508
Go on.

339
00:31:20,509 --> 00:31:22,759
Hey, hey.

340
00:31:33,306 --> 00:31:35,341
Tupper?

341
00:31:40,165 --> 00:31:44,313
He used to crawl inside
this banged up old stovepipe

342
00:31:44,314 --> 00:31:48,494
of my father's
when he was a baby.

343
00:31:48,494 --> 00:31:50,618
Miss it?

344
00:31:50,619 --> 00:31:53,720
The old country?

345
00:32:01,228 --> 00:32:03,235
No.

346
00:32:04,548 --> 00:32:07,340
It's a strange thing.

347
00:32:08,587 --> 00:32:11,555
The land here, it...

348
00:32:13,972 --> 00:32:16,073
it speaks.

349
00:32:18,494 --> 00:32:19,844
You just...

350
00:32:19,845 --> 00:32:21,945
[Clears throat]

351
00:32:27,085 --> 00:32:29,228
Listen.

352
00:32:31,697 --> 00:32:35,322
You know, sometimes
you got to go your own way.

353
00:32:35,322 --> 00:32:38,064
Sometimes it's right
to put yourself first.

354
00:32:38,064 --> 00:32:41,822
Do you know what I'm saying?

355
00:32:41,822 --> 00:32:43,446
I got enough here for now.

356
00:32:43,447 --> 00:32:45,719
There's plenty more out there.

357
00:32:45,720 --> 00:32:47,920
It's me big claim.

358
00:32:48,103 --> 00:32:50,986
- What will they do?
- I'll see them right. You'll see.

359
00:32:50,986 --> 00:32:54,658
I'll head back up, and they'll
think I struck it later.

360
00:32:55,716 --> 00:32:57,555
Why are you telling me?

361
00:32:57,556 --> 00:32:59,857
Why are you telling her what?

362
00:33:00,431 --> 00:33:01,930
You're always
sneaking up on people.

363
00:33:01,932 --> 00:33:05,641
You're always sneaking around.
You're like a lizard.

364
00:33:07,525 --> 00:33:09,893
Tell her what, Jim?

365
00:33:09,895 --> 00:33:10,969
Nothing.

366
00:33:10,970 --> 00:33:12,446
Nothing?

367
00:33:13,009 --> 00:33:16,126
You know, you're like
a little brother to me, Jimmy.

368
00:33:16,127 --> 00:33:19,298
You're like a son
to that old man in there.

369
00:33:21,197 --> 00:33:24,376
Got to sell me eights, Carver.

370
00:33:51,644 --> 00:33:53,512
[Grunts]

371
00:33:55,068 --> 00:33:57,852
[Groaning quietly]

372
00:34:05,829 --> 00:34:06,900
Come on!

373
00:34:06,900 --> 00:34:09,000
Dad!

374
00:34:38,476 --> 00:34:40,210
Quick.

375
00:34:45,788 --> 00:34:47,459
Hmm.

376
00:34:48,968 --> 00:34:50,901
Wonderful day.

377
00:34:51,280 --> 00:34:54,348
Let's load this up
for you, Tupper.

378
00:35:10,476 --> 00:35:12,327
Keep up.

379
00:35:13,202 --> 00:35:14,654
Tom.

380
00:35:14,655 --> 00:35:16,968
Don't go letting off
any stray shells.

381
00:35:16,968 --> 00:35:19,920
Keep your finger
off that trigger.

382
00:35:34,513 --> 00:35:36,181
[Gasps]

383
00:35:39,810 --> 00:35:42,061
[Chickens clucking]

384
00:35:57,819 --> 00:36:00,147
He's a fine boy.

385
00:36:00,148 --> 00:36:03,216
He's a tribute to his mother.

386
00:36:06,101 --> 00:36:08,169
Your land?

387
00:36:11,015 --> 00:36:12,998
Connolly's.

388
00:36:12,999 --> 00:36:15,820
Our illustrious local landlord.

389
00:36:16,601 --> 00:36:17,678
Peacocked.

390
00:36:17,679 --> 00:36:21,471
The best stretch
is for his bloody railroad.

391
00:36:23,151 --> 00:36:28,288
He's taking back the land and
pushing the small holders out.

392
00:36:29,187 --> 00:36:35,624
Well, let's bag something back
for the working man, shall we?

393
00:36:43,429 --> 00:36:46,206
There you go.
Privileged.

394
00:36:46,656 --> 00:36:48,179
Hey.

395
00:36:49,023 --> 00:36:50,381
That's my damper.

396
00:36:50,382 --> 00:36:52,301
What is it?

397
00:36:53,076 --> 00:36:54,983
Do you really like it here?

398
00:36:54,984 --> 00:36:56,884
Of course not.

399
00:36:57,406 --> 00:36:59,499
So why don't you go?

400
00:36:59,757 --> 00:37:01,842
I can't leave Tom.

401
00:37:01,843 --> 00:37:04,140
I'm going my own way.

402
00:37:05,797 --> 00:37:07,563
No. I can't.

403
00:37:07,781 --> 00:37:10,022
Could help you out.

404
00:37:11,289 --> 00:37:13,453
You could look after it for me,

405
00:37:14,125 --> 00:37:15,851
that thing.

406
00:37:16,761 --> 00:37:18,086
It's here with you now?

407
00:37:18,086 --> 00:37:20,251
You'd be doing me a favor.

408
00:37:21,874 --> 00:37:24,413
Can't keep it from them forever.

409
00:37:25,578 --> 00:37:29,184
They found out I had it,
I don't know what they'd do.

410
00:37:29,702 --> 00:37:32,368
Won't be good for me.
I know that.

411
00:37:33,853 --> 00:37:35,404
I'm serious.

412
00:37:36,798 --> 00:37:38,854
I have to go.

413
00:37:45,765 --> 00:37:47,967
[Spits]

414
00:37:57,111 --> 00:37:59,493
You got your possums here.

415
00:38:01,282 --> 00:38:03,816
Yes. Thank you.

416
00:38:04,236 --> 00:38:08,439
Thought you might be able to
make something nice out of them.

417
00:38:11,564 --> 00:38:15,415
They're easy enough to find
if you know where to look.

418
00:38:44,353 --> 00:38:48,056
Bet you thought I was gonna be old
Henry bloody Lawson, didn't you?

419
00:38:48,057 --> 00:38:51,456
I'll ask you to put that down,
if you don't mind.

420
00:39:24,752 --> 00:39:27,001
I thought we were gonna
shoot pigs.

421
00:39:27,002 --> 00:39:30,580
You watch that gun or you'll end up
shooting yourself in the foot.

422
00:39:30,580 --> 00:39:32,611
Wouldn't want
to have to leave you here.

423
00:39:32,612 --> 00:39:35,080
A soldier never
leaves a man behind.

424
00:39:35,080 --> 00:39:36,279
[Chuckles]

425
00:39:36,280 --> 00:39:38,493
You'd make a good soldier, Tom.

426
00:39:38,494 --> 00:39:40,214
Is that right?

427
00:39:41,298 --> 00:39:43,424
Code of honor?

428
00:39:46,010 --> 00:39:50,135
You ever do it, Henry?
You ever leave a man behind?

429
00:39:52,628 --> 00:39:55,306
Jimmy's mate back home.

430
00:39:55,307 --> 00:39:57,737
Gut wound.

431
00:39:57,737 --> 00:40:00,390
Nasty way to go.

432
00:40:01,190 --> 00:40:04,127
Boers half an hour behind us.

433
00:40:06,589 --> 00:40:08,557
What did you do?

434
00:40:09,331 --> 00:40:11,870
I made it so that
he wouldn't suffer

435
00:40:11,870 --> 00:40:14,136
more than he had to.

436
00:40:14,370 --> 00:40:16,854
Terrible thing.

437
00:40:17,854 --> 00:40:21,456
You don't understand
the meaning of "necessary"

438
00:40:21,456 --> 00:40:24,081
till you've been in a war.

439
00:40:25,667 --> 00:40:28,502
But it was the right thing to do.

440
00:40:28,831 --> 00:40:32,065
Always do the right thing, do you?

441
00:40:35,106 --> 00:40:38,158
I do what's necessary.

442
00:40:43,345 --> 00:40:47,089
We'll sit down together one day,
you and I,

443
00:40:48,260 --> 00:40:51,283
and I'll tell you some stories.

444
00:40:57,184 --> 00:40:59,552
Pigs.

445
00:41:01,284 --> 00:41:02,589
You do it.

446
00:41:02,589 --> 00:41:03,798
He's fine.

447
00:41:03,799 --> 00:41:05,339
- Go on.
- No!

448
00:41:05,339 --> 00:41:06,071
[Gunshot]

449
00:41:06,072 --> 00:41:07,994
[Pig squeals] Tom!

450
00:41:08,673 --> 00:41:10,706
[Gunshot] Whoa!

451
00:41:11,197 --> 00:41:12,900
Why don't you listen to me?

452
00:41:12,901 --> 00:41:14,963
What he hell's
the matter with you?

453
00:41:14,963 --> 00:41:16,860
Huh?

454
00:41:52,908 --> 00:41:54,525
Where is it?

455
00:41:55,048 --> 00:41:56,243
Just here.

456
00:41:56,244 --> 00:41:58,001
Show me.

457
00:42:05,072 --> 00:42:06,903
It's inside them.

458
00:42:08,509 --> 00:42:09,845
Here.

459
00:42:09,845 --> 00:42:12,204
You look after that lot

460
00:42:13,892 --> 00:42:16,306
while I go get this tested.

461
00:42:20,463 --> 00:42:23,009
Who's to say
I won't just run away with it?

462
00:42:23,010 --> 00:42:24,477
Suit yourself.

463
00:42:24,479 --> 00:42:27,103
There's plenty more
where that came from.

464
00:42:28,853 --> 00:42:31,555
- I can't.
- Of course you can.

465
00:42:31,580 --> 00:42:33,947
What's the problem, eh?

466
00:42:35,541 --> 00:42:37,831
It's what you want, isn't it?

467
00:42:38,711 --> 00:42:39,713
I have to make damper.

468
00:42:39,713 --> 00:42:40,829
Sarah, wait up.

469
00:42:40,830 --> 00:42:43,532
Let me think.
I need to think.

470
00:42:56,740 --> 00:42:59,241
[Knocking on door]

471
00:43:02,584 --> 00:43:05,071
[Indistinct chatter]

472
00:43:07,056 --> 00:43:08,586
It's my gold.

473
00:43:08,611 --> 00:43:11,189
It's here, and I can do
what I want with it.

474
00:43:11,190 --> 00:43:14,181
We can do what we want with it.

475
00:43:22,951 --> 00:43:25,767
[Breathing heavily]

476
00:43:26,821 --> 00:43:28,722
Sarah.

477
00:43:32,236 --> 00:43:34,281
Sarah.

478
00:43:36,142 --> 00:43:38,251
You're looking well, son.

479
00:43:38,252 --> 00:43:40,985
I'm feeling a lot better.
Thanks.

480
00:43:43,447 --> 00:43:44,291
Good.

481
00:43:44,291 --> 00:43:46,978
You'll be on your way
by morning, then.

482
00:44:28,747 --> 00:44:32,483
[Urine splattering]

483
00:44:46,619 --> 00:44:48,270
Tom.

484
00:44:50,719 --> 00:44:52,752
What are you doing?

485
00:44:57,525 --> 00:44:59,407
Dad!

486
00:45:08,602 --> 00:45:10,770
[Growls]

487
00:45:24,923 --> 00:45:28,212
I think it's time
for you all to go.

488
00:45:56,755 --> 00:45:59,743
[Sobbing quietly]

489
00:46:10,452 --> 00:46:13,267
[Birds singing]

490
00:46:32,072 --> 00:46:35,384
Just follow the directions
I told you. You'll be fine.

491
00:46:35,385 --> 00:46:38,813
I'd like to thank you
and your family

492
00:46:38,814 --> 00:46:41,181
for your hospitality.

493
00:46:45,692 --> 00:46:48,970
[Dog barking]

494
00:47:09,095 --> 00:47:11,837
You're not going after them?

495
00:47:18,064 --> 00:47:19,144
You can't let them go, dad.

496
00:47:19,155 --> 00:47:21,989
I'll make my own decisions.
Thank you.

497
00:47:30,228 --> 00:47:31,930
This is our future.

498
00:47:31,931 --> 00:47:33,900
- This?
- I'm your father.

499
00:47:33,900 --> 00:47:35,322
What are we going to do, dad?

500
00:47:35,347 --> 00:47:38,478
What are you going to do?

501
00:47:58,492 --> 00:48:01,314
[Groaning]

502
00:48:01,686 --> 00:48:02,860
[Gun clicks]

503
00:48:34,681 --> 00:48:35,681
[Horse neighs]

504
00:48:35,683 --> 00:48:37,282
Whoo.

505
00:48:39,056 --> 00:48:40,622
This ain't it.

506
00:48:41,009 --> 00:48:43,139
It's back there.

507
00:48:44,681 --> 00:48:46,954
That's it.

508
00:49:13,408 --> 00:49:14,666
It's a bloody dead end.

509
00:49:14,666 --> 00:49:17,133
I don't want trouble, Henry.

510
00:49:17,744 --> 00:49:21,463
When this is done,
you'll head straight that way.

511
00:49:21,463 --> 00:49:24,143
It'll take you past the river
on the high ground.

512
00:49:24,144 --> 00:49:28,197
I just want what he's got,
and then I'll be on my way.

513
00:49:28,197 --> 00:49:30,164
What are you on about?

514
00:49:30,165 --> 00:49:32,751
I need it, Henry,

515
00:49:32,752 --> 00:49:36,053
more than he does,
more than you do.

516
00:49:37,978 --> 00:49:39,752
What do you need?

517
00:49:39,752 --> 00:49:42,017
God brought you here.

518
00:49:42,431 --> 00:49:46,537
It's his will.
I need it for my family.

519
00:49:47,408 --> 00:49:49,361
Jimmy,

520
00:49:49,361 --> 00:49:51,508
give him your gold.

521
00:49:51,509 --> 00:49:53,415
What gold?

522
00:49:53,978 --> 00:49:55,564
Jimmy!

523
00:49:55,564 --> 00:49:58,533
You mongrel bastards.

524
00:49:58,533 --> 00:50:01,415
[Gunshots]

525
00:50:30,165 --> 00:50:33,626
[Vomiting]

526
00:50:46,049 --> 00:50:48,929
[Grunting]

527
00:50:53,301 --> 00:50:55,225
[Coughing]

528
00:51:12,085 --> 00:51:14,019
[Groans]

529
00:51:33,198 --> 00:51:35,824
[Piano key thumping]

530
00:51:53,394 --> 00:51:55,282
You're leaving.

531
00:51:57,621 --> 00:51:59,106
What?

532
00:51:59,113 --> 00:52:01,508
You're gonna go and leave.

533
00:52:02,035 --> 00:52:04,996
Everything's gonna be
all right now, Tom.

534
00:52:06,149 --> 00:52:07,598
I promise.

535
00:52:07,598 --> 00:52:09,654
I heard you

536
00:52:10,457 --> 00:52:11,856
with Jimmy.

537
00:52:11,858 --> 00:52:14,449
[Grunting]

538
00:52:16,887 --> 00:52:18,707
What happened?

539
00:52:19,824 --> 00:52:22,191
Where are they?

540
00:52:25,902 --> 00:52:27,711
Where have you been?

541
00:52:29,840 --> 00:52:31,871
We should never
have let them go.

542
00:52:31,872 --> 00:52:35,318
Some things are out
of our hands.

543
00:52:35,996 --> 00:52:38,362
Just gather what you need.

544
00:52:38,363 --> 00:52:41,574
Get the old trunk
out of the stable.

545
00:52:41,817 --> 00:52:44,128
[Grunting]

546
00:52:48,690 --> 00:52:50,674
Where are we going?

547
00:52:51,151 --> 00:52:53,695
- Are we leaving?
- Tom, we have to fix the cart.

548
00:52:53,964 --> 00:52:55,830
We're not going.

549
00:52:56,003 --> 00:52:56,995
Well, what's happening?

550
00:52:56,996 --> 00:52:58,150
Do as I say!

551
00:52:58,151 --> 00:52:59,549
I don't want to go!

552
00:52:59,550 --> 00:53:01,383
We have to go.

553
00:53:01,901 --> 00:53:03,853
We're not going,

554
00:53:03,854 --> 00:53:05,502
are we?

555
00:53:06,018 --> 00:53:07,506
Tom.

556
00:53:10,386 --> 00:53:12,354
You have to trust me.

557
00:53:15,870 --> 00:53:18,549
